<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,942,1215]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[189,289,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,289,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the subtribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sklenarova, Kubecek &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2014" box="[553,662,942,968]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Cautirina">Cautirina</taxonomicName>
in close relationships to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[937,1061,942,968]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Xylobanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[937,1061,942,968]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Xylobanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Laporte" authorityYear="1836" box="[1073,1172,942,968]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lycidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1926" box="[1179,1386,942,969]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Metriorrhynchini">Metriorrhynchini</taxonomicName>
), from which it can be distinguished by continuous larval terga and a simple, usually slender phallus with a pair of sickle-shaped thorns in the internal sac (
<bibRefCitation author="Sklenarova K. &amp; Kubecek V. &amp; Bocak L." box="[773,1044,1012,1039]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="37 - 54" refId="ref15307" refString="Sklenarova K., Kubecek V. &amp; Bocak L. 2014. Subtribal classification of Metriorrhynchini (Insecta: Coleoptera: Lycidae): an integrative approach using molecular phylogeny and morphology of adults and larvae. Arthropod Systematics and Phylogeny 72: 37 - 54." type="journal article" year="2014">
Sklenarova 
<emphasis box="[913,972,1013,1039]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). Almost all Oriental 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[1298,1398,1013,1039]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1298,1398,1013,1039]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the male antennae flabellate (
<figureCitation box="[592,714,1048,1074]" captionStart="Figs 2–20" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1671,1697]" captionTargetBox="[189,1396,1131,1609]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[189,1398,1126,1615]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 2–20. Cautires sp. 2. Habitus in dorsal view. 3–20. Male antennae. 3. C. alexae sp. nov. 4. C. andujari sp. nov. 5. C. arribasae sp. nov. 6. C. berembanensis sp. nov. 7. C. campestris sp. nov. 8. C. communis sp. nov. 9. C. griseus Kleine, 1930. 10. C. jasarensis sp. nov. 11. C. katarinae sp. nov. 12. C. kirstenae sp. nov. 13. C. kotatinggensis sp. nov. 14. C. linardi sp. nov. 15. C. maseki sp. nov. 16. C. pahangensis sp. nov. 17. C. nervosus Kleine, 1926. 18. C. renatae sp. nov. 19. C. reverandi Pic, 1925. 20. C. simillimus Kleine, 1926. Scale bars: Fig. 2 = 2.0 mm; Figs 3–20 = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3840230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3840230/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs 7–20</figureCitation>
), some species have very short lamellae and the antenna is acutely serrate (
<figureCitation box="[372,443,1083,1110]" captionStart="Figs 2–20" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1671,1697]" captionTargetBox="[189,1396,1131,1609]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[189,1398,1126,1615]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 2–20. Cautires sp. 2. Habitus in dorsal view. 3–20. Male antennae. 3. C. alexae sp. nov. 4. C. andujari sp. nov. 5. C. arribasae sp. nov. 6. C. berembanensis sp. nov. 7. C. campestris sp. nov. 8. C. communis sp. nov. 9. C. griseus Kleine, 1930. 10. C. jasarensis sp. nov. 11. C. katarinae sp. nov. 12. C. kirstenae sp. nov. 13. C. kotatinggensis sp. nov. 14. C. linardi sp. nov. 15. C. maseki sp. nov. 16. C. pahangensis sp. nov. 17. C. nervosus Kleine, 1926. 18. C. renatae sp. nov. 19. C. reverandi Pic, 1925. 20. C. simillimus Kleine, 1926. Scale bars: Fig. 2 = 2.0 mm; Figs 3–20 = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3840230" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3840230/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). The female antennae are always serrate. Each elytron bears four primary and five secondary longitudinal costae (
<figureCitation box="[555,690,1118,1145]" captionStart="Figs 41–58" captionStartId="9.[190,242,1822,1848]" captionTargetBox="[193,1395,820,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[189,1398,818,1776]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 41–58. Male elytra. 41. Cautires alexae sp. nov. 42. C. andujari sp. nov. 43. C. arribasae sp. nov. 44. C. berembanensis sp. nov. 45. C. campestris sp. nov. 46. C. communis sp. nov. 47. C. griseus Kleine, 1930. 48. C. jasarensis sp. nov. 49. C. katarinae sp. nov. 50. C. kirstenae sp. nov. 51. C. kotatinggensis sp. nov. 52. C. linardi sp. nov. 53. C. maseki sp. nov. 54. C. pahangensis sp. nov. 55. C. nervosus Kleine, 1926. 56. C. renatae sp. nov. 57. C. reverandi Pic, 1925. 58. C. simillimus Kleine, 1926. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3840234" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3840234/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs 41–58</figureCitation>
) and numerous transverse costae connecting them. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[1298,1398,1119,1145]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1298,1398,1119,1145]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have the lanceolate phallus with membranous internal sac bearing two sickle-shaped thorns at its base (
<figureCitation box="[292,430,1188,1215]" captionStart="Figs 59–78" captionStartId="12.[189,241,1824,1850]" captionTargetBox="[192,1392,492,1770]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[189,1398,491,1781]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 59–78. Phallus. 59. Cautires alexae sp. nov. 60. C. andujari sp. nov. 61. C. arribasae sp. nov. 62. C. berembanensis sp. nov. 63. C. campestris sp. nov. 64. C. communis sp. nov. 65. C. griseus Kleine, 1930. 66. C. jasarensis sp. nov. 67. C. katarinae sp. nov. 68. C. kirstenae sp. nov. 69. C. kotatinggensis sp. nov. 70. C. linardi sp. nov. 71. C. maseki sp. nov. 72. C. pahangensis sp. nov. 73. C. nervosus Kleine, 1926. 74. C. renatae sp. nov. 75. C. reverandi Pic, 1925. 76. C. simillimus Kleine, 1926. 77. C. selangorensis Kleine, 1930. 78. C. tenebricus Kleine, 1926. Scale bar = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3840236" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3840236/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Figs 59–78</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,292,1254,1280]" box="[189,292,1254,1280]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,292,1254,1280]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,292,1254,1280]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Remark</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,1300,1573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The revised concept of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[502,602,1301,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[502,602,1301,1327]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
merged the genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[870,1223,1300,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Bulenides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[870,986,1301,1327]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bulenides</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Waterhouse C. O." box="[1002,1223,1300,1327]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref15539" refString="Waterhouse C. O. 1879. Illustration of the Typical Specimens of Coleoptera in the Collection of the British Museum. Part I. Lycidae. British Museum, London." type="book" year="1879">Waterhouse, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1298,1398,1301,1327]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cautires</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Waterhouse C. O." box="[189,406,1336,1362]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref15539" refString="Waterhouse C. O. 1879. Illustration of the Typical Specimens of Coleoptera in the Collection of the British Museum. Part I. Lycidae. British Museum, London." type="book" year="1879">Waterhouse, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Dudkova P. &amp; Bocak L." box="[426,736,1336,1362]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="28 - 48" refId="ref14434" refString="Dudkova P. &amp; Bocak L. 2010. A review of the Cautires obsoletus species group from Indo-Burma (Coleoptera: Lycidae). Zootaxa 2527: 28 - 48." type="journal article" year="2010">Dudkova &amp; Bocak 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Later, the terminal position of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[1146,1262,1336,1362]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Bulenides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1146,1262,1336,1362]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bulenides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[189,289,1371,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,289,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade was confirmed by subsequent molecular phylogenetic study by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sklenarova K. &amp; Kubecek V. &amp; Bocak L." box="[1108,1395,1371,1397]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="37 - 54" refId="ref15307" refString="Sklenarova K., Kubecek V. &amp; Bocak L. 2014. Subtribal classification of Metriorrhynchini (Insecta: Coleoptera: Lycidae): an integrative approach using molecular phylogeny and morphology of adults and larvae. Arthropod Systematics and Phylogeny 72: 37 - 54." type="journal article" year="2014">
Sklenarova 
<emphasis box="[1247,1299,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">et al</emphasis>
. (2014)
</bibRefCitation>
. The latter study also redefined the limits of 
<taxonomicName authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[702,1046,1406,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Xylobanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[702,826,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Xylobanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Waterhouse C. O." box="[832,1046,1406,1432]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref15539" refString="Waterhouse C. O. 1879. Illustration of the Typical Specimens of Coleoptera in the Collection of the British Museum. Part I. Lycidae. British Museum, London." type="book" year="1879">Waterhouse, 1879</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which was originally defined by the absence of secondary costae. Some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[704,828,1441,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Xylobanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[704,828,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Xylobanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have elytral costae similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[1298,1398,1442,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1298,1398,1442,1468]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Cautires</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and adults of these species can be identified using the shape of male genitalia. The species group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautires" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obsoletus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">C. obsoletus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
corresponds with the limits of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[671,787,1512,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Bulenides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[671,787,1512,1538]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Bulenides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and these species differ in absence of lateral ridges in the pronotum.
</paragraph>
